The criteria for measuring the concentration of fine dust in air are based on the 'Gravimetric Method', which is a domestic process test method. 'The gravimetric method” is a method of directly (manually) measuring the mass of fine dust corresponding to a diameter of 10 μm (PM10) or 2.5 μm (PM2.5) or less, and the fine dust concentration measured in this manner is expressed in μg / m3, which represents the weight (μg) of fine dust in 1m3 of air. The fine dust measuring sensor used in indoor air quality measuring instrument and air cleaner products sold in the market is a light scattering precision sensor in an indirect way using the characteristics of light (Measuring the number and size of particles by the number and intensity of light scattering when dust enters the infrared sensing area). The gravimetric method produces accurate measured values, but expensive equipment is required, and there are limits to applying it to air cleaner products because of continuous measurement, size, etc. In the above product, we convert the amount of dust measured by applying a light-scattering type precision sensor that can measure real-time fine dust to weight. Therefore, the values of PM10 (oe) and PM2.5 (oe) indicated on the CESCO products may differ from the results obtained by 'gravimetric method”, which is the process test method depending on many complex measurement environments (airflow, temperatureㆍhumidity, air density, etc.)
